=> Datatypes in JS: Number, String, Boolean, NULL, Undefined, Objects

- NULL: null is a primitive value in JavaScript that represents the intentional absence of any object value. It means â€œnothingâ€ or â€œempty valueâ€.
- Undefined: undefined is a primitive value in JavaScript that means a variable has been declared but not assigned a value yet. Itâ€™s the default value given by JavaScript.
- Objects: An object is a collection of key-value pairs (properties). Keys are strings (or symbols), and values can be any data type, including other objects or functions.
let person = {
  name: "Ankita",
  age: 22,
  greet: function() { console.log("Hello!"); }
};
- NaN: NaN stands for â€œNot-a-Numberâ€. It is a special numeric value that represents a value that cannot be converted to a valid number.

